<i>So Andy started writing
a letter a week...</i>

733
00:56:07.114 --> 00:56:08.699
<i>...just like he said.</i>

734
00:56:12.870 --> 00:56:15.497
<i>And, just like Norton said...</i>

735
00:56:15.706 --> 00:56:17.165
<i>...Andy got no answers.</i>

736
00:56:25.382 --> 00:56:30.304
<i>The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.</i>

737
00:56:31.638 --> 00:56:33.891
<i>Year after that, he did them all...</i>

738
00:56:34.141 --> 00:56:36.059
<i>...including the warden's.</i>

739
00:56:37.811 --> 00:56:41.273
<i>Year after that,
they rescheduled the intramural season...</i>

740
00:56:41.481 --> 00:56:43.901
<i>...to coincide with tax season.</i>

741
00:56:45.485 --> 00:56:49.948
<i>The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.</i>

742
00:56:50.157 --> 00:56:51.491
So Moresby Prison ...

743
00:56:51.658 --> 00:56:53.952
... issued you a gun ,
but you paid for it.

744
00:56:54.161 --> 00:56:55.871
Right. The holster too.

745
00:56:56.079 --> 00:56:58.540
That's tax-deductible.
You can write that off.

746
00:56:58.749 --> 00:57:01.793
<i>Yes, sir.
Andy was a regular cottage industry.</i>

747
00:57:02.502 --> 00:57:07.007
<i>In fact, it got so busy at tax time,
he was allowed a staff.</i>

748
00:57:07.257 --> 00:57:09.718
Could you hand me
a stack of 1040s?

749
00:57:09.927 --> 00:57:14.765
<i>Got me out of the wood shop a month out
of the year, and that was fine by me.</i>

750
00:57:16.016 --> 00:57:19.186
<i>And still, he kept sending those letters.</i>

751
00:57:25.943 --> 00:57:26.985
It's Brooks.

752
00:57:28.111 --> 00:57:29.613
Watch the door.

753
00:57:29.863 --> 00:57:31.198
Please, Brooks.

754
00:57:31.365 --> 00:57:33.241
-Calm the fuck down .
-Stay back!

755
00:57:33.700 --> 00:57:36.328
-Stay back, goddamn it!
-What's going on?

756
00:57:36.536 --> 00:57:39.081
One second he's fine,
then out come the knife.

757
00:57:39.289 --> 00:57:41.083
We can talk about this, right?

758
00:57:41.375 --> 00:57:45.087
There's nothing to talk about.
I'll cut his fucking throat.

759
00:57:45.379 --> 00:57:47.089
What's he done to you?

760
00:57:47.297 --> 00:57:48.966
It's what they done!

761
00:57:49.466 --> 00:57:50.717
I got no choice.

762
00:57:51.218 --> 00:57:53.512
You won't hurt Heywood .
We all know that.

763
00:57:53.720 --> 00:57:56.181
-Right, Heywood?
-Sure. I know that.

764
00:57:56.390 --> 00:57:59.726
He's a friend of yours,
and Brooks is a reasonable man.

765
00:57:59.893 --> 00:58:01.103
Right, guys?

766
00:58:02.062 --> 00:58:04.564
So put the knife down .
Brooks, look at me.

767
00:58:04.731 --> 00:58:07.067
Put the knife down.

768
00:58:08.986 --> 00:58:11.071
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

769
00:58:11.822 --> 00:58:14.157
Look at his neck. He's bleeding.

770
00:58:15.075 --> 00:58:16.535
It's the only--

771
00:58:16.743 --> 00:58:18.787
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

772
00:58:19.079 --> 00:58:21.415
This is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

773
00:58:21.665 --> 00:58:23.750
Put it-- Put it down.

774
00:58:32.509 --> 00:58:34.011
Take it easy.

775
00:58:34.678 --> 00:58:36.263
You'll be all right.

776
00:58:36.430 --> 00:58:38.890
Him? What about me?

777
00:58:39.099 --> 00:58:41.476
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat!

778
00:58:41.685 --> 00:58:43.603
You've had worse from shaving.

779
00:58:43.770 --> 00:58:45.897
What did you do to set him off?

780
00:58:46.106 --> 00:58:48.316
Nothing. I come in here to say farewell.

781
00:58:48.942 --> 00:58:51.611
Ain't you heard?
His parole's come through.

782
00:58:53.780 --> 00:58:56.742
I just don't understand
what happened in there, that's all.

783
00:58:56.908 --> 00:58:59.745
Old man's crazy as a rat
in a tin shit house.

784
00:58:59.953 --> 00:59:01.830
That's enough out of you.

785
00:59:02.039 --> 00:59:04.791
-Heard he had you shitting your pants.
-Fuck you.

786
00:59:05.042 --> 00:59:06.251
Knock it off.

787
00:59:07.210 --> 00:59:08.628
Brooks ain't no bug.

788
00:59:12.466 --> 00:59:14.259
He's just institutionalized.

789
00:59:15.635 --> 00:59:17.554
"Institutionalized ," my ass.

790
00:59:17.763 --> 00:59:21.767
The man's been in here 50 years,
Heywood , 50 years!

791
00:59:21.975 --> 00:59:23.685
This is all he knows.

792
00:59:23.894 --> 00:59:26.188
In here, he's an important man ...

793
00:59:26.396 --> 00:59:27.481
...an educated man.

794
00:59:28.315 --> 00:59:30.233
Outside, he's nothing.

795
00:59:31.109 --> 00:59:34.613
Just a used-up con
with arthritis in both hands.

796
00:59:34.821 --> 00:59:37.824
Probably couldn't get a library card
if he tried.

797
00:59:38.075 --> 00:59:39.826
You know what I'm trying to say?

798
00:59:40.077 --> 00:59:42.996
I do believe
you're talking out of your ass.

799
00:59:44.247 --> 00:59:46.500
You believe whatever you want.

800
00:59:47.084 --> 00:59:49.503
But I tell you these walls are funny.

801
00:59:51.088 --> 00:59:52.756
First you hate them.

802
00:59:54.591 --> 00:59:56.510
Then you get used to them.

803
00:59:58.428 --> 01:00:00.430
Enough time passes...

804
01:00:01.098 --> 01:00:03.100
...you get so you depend on them.

805
01:00:04.101 --> 01:00:06.311
That's "institutionalized ."

806
01:00:06.520 --> 01:00:07.813
Shit.

807
01:00:08.021 --> 01:00:10.774
-I could never get like that.
-Oh , yeah?

808
01:00:11.650 --> 01:00:14.152
Wait till you've been here
as long as Brooks.

809
01:00:14.361 --> 01:00:15.946
Goddamn right.

810
01:00:18.532 --> 01:00:20.450
They send you here for life...

811
01:00:21.118 --> 01:00:23.453
...that's exactly what they take.

812
01:00:25.205 --> 01:00:27.207
Part that counts, anyway.

813
01:00:34.798 --> 01:00:37.717
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

814
01:00:38.885 --> 01:00:40.554
You go on now.

815
01:00:41.805 --> 01:00:43.306
You're free.

816
01:00:44.558 --> 01:00:46.143
You're free.

817
01:01:05.162 --> 01:01:06.830
Good luck, Brooksie.

818
01:01:09.124 --> 01:01:11.209
Take care of yourself, Brooks.

819
01:01:44.784 --> 01:01:46.286
<i>Dear fellas:</i>

820
01:01:46.578 --> 01:01:50.790
<i>I can't believe how fast things move
on the outside.</i>

821
01:01:52.083 --> 01:01:54.753
Watch it, old-timer! Want to get killed?

822
01:01:55.962 --> 01:01:59.466
<i>I saw an automobile once
when I was a kid...</i>

823
01:02:00.133 --> 01:02:02.552
<i>...but now they're everywhere.</i>

824
01:02:06.223 --> 01:02:10.518
<i>The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.</i>

825
01:02:26.326 --> 01:02:30.121
<i>The parole board
got me into this halfway house...</i>

826
01:02:30.413 --> 01:02:32.082
<i>...called "The Brewer"...</i>

827
01:02:32.290 --> 01:02:33.458
<i>...and a job...</i>

828
01:02:33.667 --> 01:02:36.628
<i>...bagging groceries at the Food-Way.</i>

829
01:02:38.171 --> 01:02:40.590
<i>It's hard work and I try to keep up...</i>

830
01:02:40.799 --> 01:02:43.176
<i>...but my hands hurt most of the time.</i>

831
01:02:43.468 --> 01:02:45.428
Make sure your man double-bags.

832
01:02:45.637 --> 01:02:47.681
Last time, the bottom near came out.

833
01:02:48.348 --> 01:02:51.268
Make sure you double-bag
like the lady says. Understand?

834
01:02:51.476 --> 01:02:52.852
Yes, sir. Surely will.

835
01:02:53.019 --> 01:02:56.564
<i>I don't think the store manager
likes me very much.</i>

836
01:02:59.567 --> 01:03:03.863
<i>Sometimes after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.</i>

837
01:03:04.322 --> 01:03:05.824
<i>I keep thinking...</i>

838
01:03:06.032 --> 01:03:09.369
<i>...Jake might just show up
and say hello.</i>

839
01:03:09.995 --> 01:03:11.997
<i>But he never does.</i>

840
01:03:13.206 --> 01:03:18.044
<i>I hope, wherever he is, he's doing okay
and making new friends.</i>

841
01:03:21.673 --> 01:03:24.384
<i>I have trouble sleeping at night.</i>

842
01:03:24.718 --> 01:03:27.971
<i>I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.</i>

843
01:03:28.221 --> 01:03:30.473
<i>I wake up scared.</i>

844
01:03:30.682 --> 01:03:34.894
<i>Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.</i>

845
01:03:36.396 --> 01:03:41.318
<i>Maybe I should get me a gun and rob
the Food-Way so they'd send me home.</i>

846
01:03:41.609 --> 01:03:45.947
<i>I could shoot the manager while
I was at it. Sort of like a bonus.</i>

847
01:03:47.615 --> 01:03:51.619
<i>I guess I'm too old
for that sort of nonsense anymore.</i>

848
01:03:51.870 --> 01:03:53.580
<i>I don't like it here.</i>

849
01:03:53.788 --> 01:03:57.792
<i>I'm tired of being afraid all the time.
I've decided...</i>

850
01:03:58.626 --> 01:04:00.295
<i>...not to stay.</i>

851
01:04:11.222 --> 01:04:13.767
<i>I doubt they'll kick up any fuss...</i>

852
01:04:13.975 --> 01:04:17.479
<i>...not for an old crook like me.</i>

853
01:05:19.958 --> 01:05:24.212
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss,
not for an old crook like me.

854
01:05:25.255 --> 01:05:29.092
P.S. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

855
01:05:29.300 --> 01:05:31.636
No hard feelings. Brooks."

856
01:05:42.105 --> 01:05:44.065
He should have died in here.

857
01:05:49.612 --> 01:05:51.030
What the fuck have you done?

858
01:05:51.197 --> 01:05:53.867
It's a goddamn mess,
I'll tell you that.

859
01:05:59.414 --> 01:06:03.168
-What's all this?
-You tell me. They're addressed to you.

860
01:06:04.419 --> 01:06:05.753
Take it.

861
01:06:14.304 --> 01:06:15.805
"Dear Mr. Dufresne:

862
01:06:16.931 --> 01:06:18.892
In response to your repeated inquiries...

863
01:06:19.100 --> 01:06:23.396
...the state has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project."

864
01:06:24.147 --> 01:06:25.982
This is $200.

865
01:06:26.191 --> 01:06:30.195
"In addition , the library district
has generously responded ...

866
01:06:30.403 --> 01:06:32.947
...with a donation of used books
and sundries.

867
01:06:33.156 --> 01:06:37.285
We trust this will fill your needs.
We now consider the matter closed.

868
01:06:37.494 --> 01:06:39.370
Please stop sending us letters."

869
01:06:39.537 --> 01:06:42.207
Clear all this out
before the warden gets back.

870
01:06:42.415 --> 01:06:43.583
Yes, sir.

871
01:06:47.879 --> 01:06:49.047
Good for you , Andy.

872
01:06:54.344 --> 01:06:56.262
It only took six years.

873
01:06:57.847 --> 01:07:00.600
From now on , I'll write two
letters a week instead of one.

874
01:07:00.767 --> 01:07:04.103
I believe you're crazy enough .
Get this stuff out...

875
01:07:04.395 --> 01:07:06.814
... like he said .
I've got to pinch a loaf.

876
01:07:07.023 --> 01:07:08.483
When I come back...

877
01:07:08.691 --> 01:07:10.443
...this is all gone, all right?

878
01:07:59.200 --> 01:08:00.618
Do you hear that?

879
01:09:09.354 --> 01:09:10.521
Dufresne!

880
01:09:13.066 --> 01:09:14.567
Andy, let me out!

881
01:09:21.449 --> 01:09:26.412
<i>I have no idea to this day what those
two Italian ladies were singing about.</i>

882
01:09:26.704 --> 01:09:28.915
<i>Truth is, I don't want to know.</i>

883
01:09:29.123 --> 01:09:31.626
<i>Some things are best left unsaid.</i>

884
01:09:35.213 --> 01:09:37.924
<i>I like to think it was something
so beautiful...</i>

885
01:09:38.132 --> 01:09:40.259
<i>...it can't be expressed in words...</i>

886
01:09:40.468 --> 01:09:43.388
<i>...and makes your heart ache
because of it.</i>

887
01:09:45.056 --> 01:09:47.558
<i>I tell you, those voices soared...</i>

888
01:09:47.809 --> 01:09:52.105
<i>...higher and farther than anybody
in a gray place dares to dream.</i>

889
01:09:52.313 --> 01:09:55.692
<i>It was like a beautiful bird
flapped into our drab cage...</i>

890
01:09:55.900 --> 01:09:58.653
<i>...and made those walls dissolve away.</i>

891
01:09:59.112 --> 01:10:01.280
<i>And for the briefest of moments...</i>

892
01:10:01.489 --> 01:10:04.492
<i>...every last man at Shawshank felt free.</i>

893
01:10:07.078 --> 01:10:09.747
<i>It pissed the warden off
something awful.</i>

894
01:10:11.040 --> 01:10:12.041
Open the door.

895
01:10:14.961 --> 01:10:16.713
Open it up!

896
01:10:18.005 --> 01:10:20.758
Dufresne, open this door!

897
01:10:22.093 --> 01:10:23.302
Turn that off!

898
01:10:30.351 --> 01:10:32.812
I am warning you. Turn that off!

899
01:10:50.538 --> 01:10:52.081
You're mine now.

900
01:10:59.505 --> 01:11:02.759
<i>Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.</i>

901
01:11:02.967 --> 01:11:04.552
On your feet.

902
01:11:05.720 --> 01:11:08.139
-Hey, look who's here.
-Maestro!

903
01:11:09.891 --> 01:11:13.561
You couldn't play something good , huh?
Like Hank Williams?

904
01:11:13.895 --> 01:11:16.689
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

905
01:11:16.898 --> 01:11:20.026
-Was it worth two weeks?
-Easiest time I ever did.

906
01:11:20.234 --> 01:11:24.447
-No such thing as easy time in the hole.
-A week in the hole is like a year.

907
01:11:24.655 --> 01:11:27.950
-Damn straight.
-I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

908
01:11:28.159 --> 01:11:31.120
So they let you tote
that record player down there, huh?

909
01:11:33.539 --> 01:11:34.916
It was in here.

910
01:11:35.750 --> 01:11:37.001
In here.

911
01:11:38.127 --> 01:11:40.213
That's the beauty of music. They...

912
01:11:40.421 --> 01:11:42.757
...can't get that from you.

913
01:11:46.302 --> 01:11:48.679
Haven't you ever felt
that way about music?

914
01:11:50.473 --> 01:11:53.601
Well , I played a mean harmonica
as a younger man.

915
01:11:54.644 --> 01:11:56.354
Lost interest in it, though.

916
01:11:56.562 --> 01:11:58.147
Didn't make much sense in here.

917
01:11:58.481 --> 01:12:00.483
Here's where it makes the most sense.

918
01:12:01.025 --> 01:12:03.069
You need it so you don't forget.

919
01:12:03.653 --> 01:12:04.946
Forget?

920
01:12:05.238 --> 01:12:08.324
Forget that there are...

921
01:12:08.533 --> 01:12:09.951
... places...

922
01:12:10.451 --> 01:12:14.288
... in the world
that aren't made out of stone.

923
01:12:15.289 --> 01:12:16.791
There's something ...

924
01:12:17.124 --> 01:12:18.543
... inside...

925
01:12:18.793 --> 01:12:20.753
...that they can't get to...

926
01:12:20.962 --> 01:12:22.380
...that they can't touch.

927
01:12:22.880 --> 01:12:24.298
That's yours.

928
01:12:25.842 --> 01:12:27.426
What are you talking about?

929
01:12:28.469 --> 01:12:29.720
Hope.

930
01:12:30.763 --> 01:12:32.098
Hope.

931
01:12:34.058 --> 01:12:36.060
Let me tell you something , my friend.

932
01:12:36.853 --> 01:12:39.146
Hope is a dangerous thing.

933
01:12:40.314 --> 01:12:42.650
Hope can drive a man insane.

934
01:12:43.401 --> 01:12:45.528
It's got no use on the inside.

935
01:12:45.736 --> 01:12:47.947
You'd better get used to that idea.

936
01:12:50.449 --> 01:12:51.951
Like Brooks did?

937
01:13:17.310 --> 01:13:18.311
Sit down.

938
01:13:23.649 --> 01:13:26.944
Says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

939
01:13:28.112 --> 01:13:30.156
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

940
01:13:30.364 --> 01:13:31.616
Oh , yes, sir.

941
01:13:32.867 --> 01:13:34.201
Without a doubt.

942
01:13:35.369 --> 01:13:37.788
I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

943
01:13:39.790 --> 01:13:41.709
No danger to society here.

944
01:13:42.251 --> 01:13:43.794
God's honest truth.

945
01:13:46.339 --> 01:13:48.466
Absolutely rehabilitated.

946
01:13:58.434 --> 01:13:59.769
Thirty years.

947
01:14:01.729 --> 01:14:03.648
Jesus, when you say it like that...

948
01:14:04.523 --> 01:14:06.317
You wonder where it went.

949
01:14:08.736 --> 01:14:10.905
I wonder where 10 years went.

950
01:14:15.868 --> 01:14:16.911
Here.

951
01:14:17.370 --> 01:14:20.081
A little parole rejection present.

952
01:14:21.374 --> 01:14:23.042
Go ahead and open it.

953
01:14:24.168 --> 01:14:26.212
Went through one of your competitors.

954
01:14:26.379 --> 01:14:29.548
I hope you don't mind .
I wanted it to be a surprise.

955
01:14:39.558 --> 01:14:41.060
It's very pretty.

956
01:14:42.770 --> 01:14:43.980
Thank you.

957
01:14:46.565 --> 01:14:48.025
You going to play it?

958
01:14:52.571 --> 01:14:53.864
No.

959
01:14:57.451 --> 01:14:58.869
Not right now.

960
01:15:16.554 --> 01:15:17.638
Roll in!

961
01:15:53.841 --> 01:15:55.092
Lights out!

962
01:16:29.668 --> 01:16:31.837
<i>Andy was as good as his word.</i>

963
01:16:32.171 --> 01:16:34.965
<i>He wrote two letters a week
instead of one.</i>

964
01:16:37.009 --> 01:16:41.138
<i>In 1959, the state senate
finally clued in to the fact...</i>

965
01:16:41.347 --> 01:16:44.517
<i>...they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.</i>

966
01:16:44.683 --> 01:16:49.021
<i>Appropriations Committee
voted an annual payment of $500...</i>

967
01:16:49.188 --> 01:16:51.107
<i>...just to shut him up.</i>

968
01:16:51.315 --> 01:16:54.318
<i>And you'd be amazed how far
Andy could stretch it.</i>

969
01:16:54.527 --> 01:16:57.446
<i>He made deals with book clubs,
charity groups.</i>

970
01:16:57.655 --> 01:17:00.407
<i>He bought remaindered books
by the pound...</i>

971
01:17:00.908 --> 01:17:02.451
<i>Treasure island.</i>

972
01:17:02.993 --> 01:17:04.328
Robert Louis--

973
01:17:04.537 --> 01:17:05.538
Stevenson.

974
01:17:05.746 --> 01:17:07.164
Fiction , adventure.

975
01:17:09.708 --> 01:17:10.751
What's next?

976
01:17:10.918 --> 01:17:14.004
